------|---------|-----------|\n| Base model | OpenCode (GLM-5) | OpenCode (GLM-5) |\n| Default skills | Standard skillset | Standard skillset |\n| Additional skills | None | laws-of-simplicity |\n| Temperature | 0.0 | 0.0 |\n| Max tokens | Unlimited | Unlimited |\n\n### Execution Protocol\n\n1. For each task T in benchmark:\n   - Initialize fresh context for Control run\n   - Execute task, record all tokens (input/output)\n   - Initialize fresh context for Treatment run\n   - Execute task, record all tokens\n   - Run test suite to verify success\n\n2. Exclude tasks that timeout (>10 minutes) or error irrecoverably\n\n### Environment\n\n- Isolated containers per run (prevent context leakage)\n- Consistent hardware/API endpoints for all runs\n- Automated logging of token counts, tool calls, timestamps\n\n### Reproducibility\n\n- All prompts, skill files, and configurations versioned in git\n- Experiment runner scripts provided as supplementary material\n- Benchmark task IDs and results logged for verification\n\n## Metrics and Measurement\n\n### Primary Metrics\n\n| Metric | Definition | Measurement |\n|--------|-------------|-------------|\n| **Input tokens** | Tokens sent to model | API response headers |\n| **Output tokens** | Tokens generated by model | API response headers |\n| **Total tokens** | Input + Output | Computed |\n| **Token delta** | Control - Treatment per task | Computed |\n\n### Secondary Metrics\n\n| Metric | Definition | Measurement |\n|--------|-------------|-------------|\n| **Success rate** | Tasks passing test suite | Automated test runner |\n| **Time per task** | Wall-clock time from start to completion | Timestamp logging |\n| **Time distribution** | Histogram of completion times per condition | Statistical distribution analysis |\n| **Iteration count** | Number of agent reasoning cycles | Tool call sequences logged |\n\n### Time Distribution Analysis\n\n- Plot side-by-side histograms (Control vs Treatment)\n- Report median, mean, 95th percentile\n- Statistical test: Mann-Whitney U test for distribution difference\n- This captures whether simplicity guidance accelerates convergence\n\n### Qualitative Metrics (for RQ3)\n\n| Metric | Definition | Measurement |\n|--------|------------|-------------|\n| **Task complexity category** | Simple/Medium/Complex based on LoC changed | Benchmark metadata |\n| **Code simplicity score** | Lines of code, cyclomatic complexity | Static analysis tools |\n\n### Data Collection\n\n- JSON logs per task: `{task_id, condition, input_tokens, output_tokens, success, time_seconds, iterations}`\n- Aggregated into CSV for statistical analysis\n\n## Statistical Analysis\n\n### RQ1 Analysis (Token Reduction)\n\n- Paired t-test on total tokens (Control vs Treatment per task)\n- Report: mean difference, 95% CI, Cohen's d (effect size)\n- Significance threshold: p < 0.05\n\n### RQ2 Analysis (Success Rate)\n\n- McNemar's test for paired success/failure outcomes\n- Report: success rate per condition, p-value\n- Null hypothesis: skill does not affect success probability\n\n### RQ3 Analysis (Task Categories)\n\n- Stratified analysis by task complexity (Simple/Medium/Complex)\n- Two-way ANOVA: Condition x Complexity\n- Post-hoc pairwise comparisons with Bonferroni correction\n\n### Time Distribution Analysis\n\n- Mann-Whitney U test (non-parametric, handles skewed distributions)\n- Report: median difference, effect size (rank-biserial correlation)\n- Visual: overlaid density plots, box plots\n\n### Confidence Intervals\n\n- Bootstrap 95% CI for all effect sizes\n- Report both frequentist p-values and Bayesian posterior probabilities\n\n### Result Presentation\n\n- **Table 1:** Descriptive statistics (mean, SD, median per condition)\n- **Table 2:** Statistical test results with effect sizes\n- **Figure 1:** Token reduction distribution (Control - Treatment)\n- **Figure 2:** Time-to-completion histograms (overlaid)\n\n## Paper Structure\n\n### Title\n\"On the Impact of Laws of Simplicity Skill on the Efficiency of AI Coding Agents\"\n\n### Abstract\n- Background: AI coding agents increasingly used for software development\n- Problem: Agents may over-engineer, consuming unnecessary tokens\n- Approach: Laws of Simplicity skill to guide toward simpler solutions\n- Method: Controlled A/B experiment on SWE-bench and HumanEval\n- Results: [To be filled after experiment]\n- Conclusion: [To be filled after experiment]\n\n### Sections\n\n1. **Introduction**\n   - Rise of AI coding agents\n   - Token efficiency as a cost and sustainability concern\n   - Laws of Simplicity as a design philosophy\n   - Research questions\n\n2. **Background**\n   - AI coding agents landscape\n   - SWE-bench and similar benchmarks\n   - John Maeda's Laws of Simplicity\n   - Related work on agent efficiency\n\n3. **Methodology**\n   - Experimental design\n   - Benchmarks and agent selection\n   - Metrics and measurement\n   - Statistical analysis approach\n\n4. **Results**\n   - Token consumption comparison\n   - Success rate analysis\n   - Time distribution analysis\n   - Task category breakdown\n\n5. **Discussion**\n   - Interpretation of findings\n   - Implications for practice\n   - Threats to validity\n   - Limitations\n\n6. **Conclusion**\n   - Summary of contributions\n   - Future work\n\n## Timeline\n\n| Phase | Duration | Tasks |\n|-------|-----------|-------|\n| Setup | 1 week | Implement experiment runner, configure environments |\n| Data Collection | 2-3 weeks | Run experiments, collect logs |\n| Analysis | 1 week | Statistical analysis, generate figures |\n| Writing | 1 week | Draft paper, iterate |\n| Review | 1 week | Internal review, revisions |\n| Submission | - | Submit to arXiv |\n\n## Deliverables\n\n1. Research paper (PDF, LaTeX source)\n2. Experiment runner scripts\n3. Raw data (JSON logs)\n4. Analysis scripts (Python/R)\n5. Reproducibility package (Docker container, dependencies)\n\n## Success Criteria\n\n- Statistically significant token reduction (p < 0.05)\